<br>
I am very distressed by the current tension between the french and US people. Whatever the politicians do on both sides, it kinda sickens me to see we are throwing so much mud on each other. I stayed in the US as a tourist and exchange student, was hosted by very kind american families, had a american GF, and have long time american friends. I just can't stand seeing us ripping each other.<br>
<br>
 Here in France we have a good potion of the public opinion convinced you are fighting a colonisation war to occupy iraq and get it's oil secured and for free. On your side many americans are convinced we were defending SH to secure oil contracts and get bills paid for equipment. <br>
<br>
I did a little fact finding : <br>
The oil company TOTAL drafted a contract with iraq, which wasn't signed, to exploit oil there. It was drafted in the event the embargo would be lifted. We bought petrol from iraq through the UN. The US, last year, bought 50% of the iraqi oil production through the UN. (found that on the department of energy website).<br>
<br>
I can tell you the average frenchman doesn't give a shet about this iraq debt problem. Anti war opinion in France is primarily motivated by a very big taboo which is that a preemptive war is unacceptable. This taboo goes back to the cold war, when everyone knew that the country who would attack another one belonging to the other side of the iron curtain, would risk total destruction of all Europe. <br>
<br>
The french opinion is also very shortsighted about the US at the moment. Reducing the US motivation to a greed motivated war to seize iraq's oil reserves is a very partial view of the real problem. <br>
<br>
It is very comfortable for us french and americans to just ingest the caned dogma our respective media is spewing about the other side, greedy selfish and power grabing. We will not rebuild a good relationship on these basis. <br>
<br>
I am angered by our 2 governements, who were unable to work out an intelligent solution about iraq, and are currently leting their respective public opinions ripping each other to shreds. Bush really was too blunt and arrogant trying to force the UN approval and Chirac , a very talented demagogist, tried to be a 2nd De Gaulle, without the talent and vista his illustrious predecessor had. The net result is that Russia and China are most certainly laughing there heads off seing the western countries in shambles now.  <br>
<br>
Both people will have to rebuild a relationship, it is of paramount importance as the world will be much more fucked up in the future. <br>
<br>
In the meanwhile, I can tell you I sincerely hope you win the war with the less casualties both for your soldiers and the civilians there. I hope your troops will not have to stay there for peacekeeping for too long as I fear you will encounter many problems with suicide bombers and guerilla fighters. The best thing would be to void all the existing oil contracts the SH governement had signed be they russian, french or whatever. Then the UN could step in and administer iraq, fund rebuilding with every nation giving money. The contractors would be chosen on pure technical and economical criterias, without any regard to their nationality. A part of the funding raised could be channeled to the US and UK as a participation to their war effort.<br>
<br>
Then all the western countries will have to press their efforts onto the arab/israel problem to force a peaceful solution as i believe it is the true cancer that is destroying the middle east.<br>
And we ll need the combined strenght of the US and Europe to do that.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Uhuru Shirokinukatsukami<br>
Transcendent in Raging Fury<br>
